Denote by $h$ the height of the equilateral triangle, by $b$ one of its sides. Points $B$ and $A$ have equal $y$-coordinates, which implies their midpoint $M$ has $y$-coordinate $\tfrac{-h}{2}$ as well. Since $M$ has $x$-coordinate one third of $b$, we conclude $M=\left(\tfrac{b}{3},\tfrac{-h}{2}\right)$. Thus $\tfrac{-h}{2}=-\tfrac{1}{2}\cdot \left(\tfrac{1}{3}b\right)^2$, or equivalently, $\boxed{h=\tfrac{9}{2}b^2}$.From right triangle $ABM$ we obtain by Pythagorean theorem
\[\left(\tfrac{b}{3}\right)^2+h^2=b^2 \quad\Longrightarrow\quad \tfrac{b^2}{9}+\left(\tfrac{9}{2}b^2\right)=b^2 \quad\boxed{\Rightarrow}\quad \boxed{b=2\sqrt{11}}.\end{think}

The length of one side of the equilateral triangle is $\boxed{2\sqrt{11}}$.

